title: Determination of Differential Elastic and Inelastic and Double-differential Neutron Scattering Cross Sections of Elemental Copper at Energies between 6.95 MeV and 14.18 MeV.

x4freetext: Sections of Elemental Copper at Energies between
Turnable CV-28 compact cyclotron (1 ns pulse
Deuterium gas target, 1.0 cm in diameter and
3.0 cm in length, gas pressure 1.9-2.0 hPa. Mean
neutron energy is defined within +/- 20 keV.
n/gamma discrimination with pulse shape analysis.
Five NE213 neutron detectors D1-D5 located
behind a massive collimator shielding in a distance
of 1200 cm from the sample. The angle separation
between the detectors is 12.5 deg., diameter 10.16 cm
(D2-D5). The angle region covered is 12.5 deg to
.An additional NE213 detector was used as relative
fluence monitor, diameter 3.81 cm, length 3.81 cm.
The movable monitor (in a fixed distance of 651 cm)
was always in a position of 58.9 deg relative
diameter 25.0 mm, height 51.5 mm, mass 224.37 g,
placed 17.5 cm from the gas target centre. Isotopic
abundance of Cu-63 is 69.2% and of Cu-65 is 30.8%.
.Monte Carlo simulated TOF spectra of the complete
angular distribution were iteratively adjusted to
the measured TOF spectra. The simulation comprised
the neutron production in the gas target and the
scattering geometry between target, sample and
.Parasitic neutrons from the D(d,np) breakup reaction
were simulated and subtracted. The data for the
simulation were adjusted by additional measurements
of the neutron scattering with a 4-He(d,np) neutron
<ERR-T>  Total errors comprise counting statistics and
Error of the central point of neutron energy
. An additional uncertainty of 5% of the ratio
N-bu/N-in is taken into account for the DDX
neutrons, N-in = fraction of inelastically scattered
.Inelastic cross sections were extracted based on
the assumption of an isotopic abundance of Cu-63
Inelastic cross sections were determined for the
levels 0.670 MeV and 0.962 MeV (Cu-63) and for the
The levels 1.327 MeV and 1.412 MeV (Cu-63) and
excitation energy 1.41 MeV), and the sum cross section
was treated as elemental cross section. The inelastic
scattering for higher-lying levels was treated as DDX.
